JOHANNESBURG - The South African Federation of Trade Unions said it is disappointed with government's response to the novel coronavirus, particularly as it comes to fixing the country's already ailing economy. READ: COVID-19: Rwanda imposes shutdown The Fix's Karima Brown spoke to the Union's general secretary, Zwelinzima Vavi, who said frontline workers have complained of the speed of the response from the government. Vavi said even among medical professionals, there have not been sufficient education and training in managing people who think they have symptoms. The Saftu general secretary called for greater compliance in large industries like mining.